						<question>
							<title>How will each item of work be assessed?</title>
							<p>
								Unlike "typical" college courses, there are no points or partial credit to be earned in this course. Instead, each item of work will come with its own <term>specifications</term> for completing the item at one of four potential levels, each of which is given an approximate interpretation below:
								<ul>
									<li><em>E</em>xceeds expectations: this work is submitted on time, is extremely well done, clearly communicated, and could function as the official class solution.</li>
									<li><em>M</em>eets expectations: this work is generally correct, but either contains some minor mathematical errors which do not detract from the overall solution, or contains some unclear/incomplete communication.</li>
									<li><em>R</em>evision needed: the work contains some significant errors and/or the guidelines for preparing and presenting the solution were not followed, but you seem to be on the right track toward a passing grade.</li>
									<li><em>N</em>ot assessable: the work was not turned in on time, is difficult to read, or contains significant enough flaws that you're probably better starting over.</li>
								</ul>
								Generally, E's and M's are considered <em>passing</em>, while R's and N's are not. Some assessments will be graded on a 2-level rubric (such as group presentations), some on a 3-level (such as the Rubik's cube quiz), and others on a 4-level (such as the other MFA's).
							</p>
						</question>
					
