    <part xml:id="Part-Play">
		<title>Play</title>
		<introduction>
			<p>
				One of the fundamental human desires is for <em>play</em>.
				In recent years, ancient games and puzzles such as Go, Nim, and Chess have given way to a slew of <url href="http://boardgamegeek.com">new games</url>, many of which can be understood and analyzed with mathematical thinking.
			
				In this part, we explore play in two contexts: the classic Rubik's cube puzzle, and the game of chess.
				Our exploration of the Rubik's cube is heavily inspired by the <url href="https://www.artofmathematics.org">Art of Mathematics</url> project.
			</p>
		</introduction>

		<chapter xml:id="Chap-RubiksCube">
		  <title>The Rubik's Cube</title>
