				<li>Therefore, <m>Q</m></li>
			</ul>
			
			<p>
				A closely related rule of inference is known as <term>modus tollens</term>, and runs thusly:
			</p>
			<ul>
				<li>If <m>P</m>, then <m>Q</m>.</li>
				<li>Not <m>Q</m>,</li>
				<li>Therefore, not <m>P</m>.</li>
			</ul>
 ~~>
 -->
				
				<p>
					We have seen thus far a way of formalizing logic so that we can think about the truth of a statement purely syntactically (structurally) without regard for the semantic meaning of the statements under consideration.
					In the late 19th century, mathematicians developed what became known as <term>formal systems</term>, consisting of axioms, which were strings of symbols, such as
					<me>
						\exists B \forall C, (C\in B \Leftrightarrow C\subseteq A),
					</me>
					along with a <term>logical calculus</term>, which govern the rules of inference that can be used on the axioms to deduce new theorems.
				</p>
				
				<p>
					Further, mathematicians had long assumed there were consistent foundational axioms for their discipline.
					Newly discovered paradoxes challenged this view.
				</p>
				<exploration>
					<title>Russell's Paradox</title>
					<p>
						In a certain town lives a barber who only cuts the hair of <em>all</em> people who do not cut their own hair.
						Who cuts the barber's hair?
					</p>
					<solution>
						<p>
							This is a paradox: if the barber cuts his own hair, we reach a contradiction, as he only cuts the hair of those who do not cut their own hair. On the other hand, if the barber does not cut his own hair, he does by definition.
						</p>
						<p>
							This sort of self-referential paradox is exactly the sort that we'll study later in this section that led to the foundational crisis referred to in the section title.
						</p>
					</solution>
				</exploration>
				
				<p>
					Two main schools of mathematical philosophy sprung up in the wake of these discoveries.
					The <term>formalists</term> argued that statements of mathematics and logic are really just about the rules and consequences for manipulating symbols and strings of letters.
					That is, mathematics does not have a subject matter at all--just empty symbols, which may be given an interpretation in particular situations and thus have meaning.
				</p>
				<p>
					The response came from the <term>intuitionists</term>.
					Intuitionism is an approach that consideres mathematics to be purely the result of the constructive mental activity of humans rather than the discovery of any principles which we can reasonably claim exist in an objective reality.
					Thus, in some sense, mathematics is up to whoever is doing the mathematics.
					To the intuitionists, the formalists were reducing mathematics to a meaningless game with symbols.
				</p>
				
				<principle>
					<p>
						Do you resonate more with a formalist approach to mathematics, or an intuitionist approach?
						Relatedly: do you believe mathematics is something humans invent, or something we discover in the creation?
						Why?
					</p>
				</principle>


				<p>
					In 1900, at the second International Congress of Mathematicians in Paris, the esteemed mathematician David Hilbert posed 23 theretofore unanswered problems in mathematics that he thought were important to guide the development of mathematics in the 20th century.
					We've already seen one of them (the 8th): the Goldbach conjecture.
					Most of Hilbert's problems have been solved, but three are unresolved, two are thought to be too vague to ever get consensus on what a solution would look like, and one is the subject of much debate.
				</p>
				<p>					
					In an attempt to resolve the issues raised by paradoxes like Russell's Paradox, Hilbert posed this problem, the second on the list:
				</p>
				<blockquote>
					But above all I wish to designate the following as the most important among the numerous questions which can be asked with regard to the axioms: To prove that they are not contradictory, that is, that a definite number of logical steps based upon them can never lead to contradictory results….
				</blockquote>
				
				<p>
					That is, Hilbert wanted mathematicians to prove that the axioms on which mathematics was founded did not lead to a contradiction.
					The resolution to this problem is surprising, and to begin to explore it, we will return to Smullyan Island.
					Recall <xref ref="axiom-smullyan" />.
				</p>
				
				<exploration>
					<statement>
						<p>
							While visiting Smullyan Island, we meet two natives, Corrie and Will.
							Will says, "Corrie is a knave."
							Corrie says, "Exactly one of us is a knight."
							What are Corrie and Will?
						</p>
					</statement>
					<solution>
						<p>
							We may begin by supposing Corrie is a knave<fn>Though we could assume either one is a knight or a knave.</fn>.
							In that case, her statement is false, and there must be 0 or 2 knights.
							But if Corrie is a knave, there cannot be 2 knights, so there must be 0 knights, in which case Will's statement is false.
							However, this leads us to the conclusion that Corrie is a knight, yet we began by assuming that she is a knave.
							</p>

							<p>
								This contradiction forces us to conclude that Corrie is a knight, and her statement implies that she is the only knight.
								Thus, Will is a knave.
							</p>

					</solution>

				</exploration>
				
				<exploration>
					<statement>
						<p>
							While visiting Smullyan Island, you meet three people: Abbie, Bart, and Cate.
							Abbie says, "Cate is a knave".
							Bart says, "None of us are knaves."
							Cate says, "Bart is a knight."
							What are Abbie, Bart, and Cate?
						</p>
					</statement>
					<solution>
						<p>
							Begin by supposing Abbie is a knave.
							Then Cate must be a knight, whereby Bart is a knight; but this cannot be, because it would force Bart's statement to be true, contradicting the assumption that Abbie is a knave.
							Therefore, Abbie is a knight.
							</p>
						<p>
							Since Abbie is a knight, Cate is a knave, whereby Bart must be a knave as well.
						</p>
					</solution>


				</exploration>
				
				
				<p>
					For the explorations that follow, recall that the only way in which the implication <m>P\Rightarrow Q</m> is false is if <m>P</m> is true but <m>Q</m> is false; see <xref ref="def-implications" /> and the ensuing discussion for more.
				</p>
				
				<exploration xml:id="expl-knavessay">
					<statement>
						<p>
							Consider the following questions about knaves on Smullyan Island.
						</p>
						<ol>
							<li>Can a knave say, "If I am a knight, then there is gold on Smullyan Island?" Explain.</li>
							<li>Can a knave say, "If I am a knight, then <m>1+1=3</m>?" Explain.</li>
							<li>Can a knave say, "If I am a knight, then <m>Q</m>," for any statement <m>Q</m>? Explain.</li>
						</ol>
					</statement>
					<solution>
						<p>
							We had an in-depth discussion on this, and it all hinges on what it means for the implication <m>P\Rightarrow Q</m> to be true. Since a knave can only say false statements, the knave can only say things of the form <m>P \Rightarrow Q</m> when <m>P</m> is true but <m>Q</m> is false.
							Since the statement <m>P = \text{"I am a knight"}</m> is false, the knave cannot say anything of this form, regardless of the truth or falsity of <m>Q</m>.
						</p>
					</solution>
				</exploration>
				
				
				<exploration xml:id="expl-knightssay">
					<statement>
						<p>
							Consider the following questions about knights on Smullyan Island.
						</p>
						<ol>
							<li>Can a knight say, "If I am a knight, then there is gold on Smullyan Island" if there is no gold on the island? Explain.</li>
							<li>Can a knight say, "If I am a knight, then <m>1+1=3</m>?" Explain.</li>
							<li>Can a knight say, "If I am a knight, then <m>Q</m>," for any false statement <m>Q</m>? Explain.</li>
						</ol>

					</statement>
					<solution>
						<p>
							The big take-away from this exploration is that knights cannot say anything of the form "If I am a knight, then <m>Q</m>" if <m>Q</m> is false. This puts us in row 2 of the truth table for <m>P\Rightarrow Q</m> defined in <xref ref="def-implications" />, which is the only way for <m>P\Rightarrow Q</m> to be false.
						</p>
					</solution>
				</exploration>
				
				<principle>
					<statement>
						<p>
							If a native of Smullyan Island makes a statement of the form "If I am a knight, then <m>Q</m>" for some statement <m>Q</m>, what can you conclude about the native and the truth or falsity of <m>Q</m>? Why?
						</p>
					</statement>
					<solution>
						<p>
							Since knaves can't say anything of this form, and knights can't say it when <m>Q</m> is false, we can conclude that the native is a knight and that <m>Q</m> is true.
						</p>
					</solution>
				</principle>
				
				<p>
					Our exploration of the major developments in 20th century mathematical logic will hinge on a careful analysis of statements of the form "You will/will not believe that...".
					So, we turn to an initial analysis of such statements.
				</p>

				
				<activity>
					<statement>
						<ol>
							<li>Suppose you meet a native who you believe is a knight, and the native says, "There is gold on Smullyan Island."
							Do you go searching for gold? Explain.</li>
							<li>Suppose you meet a native who you believe is a knave, and the native says, "There is gold on Smullyan Island."
							Do you go searching for gold? Explain.</li>
							<li>Can any inhabitant of Smullyan Island ever say, "I am not a knight?" Explain.</li>
							<li>Suppose you meet a native who you believe is a knight, and the native says, "You will believe that I have a pot of gold." What do you believe? Explain.</li>
							<li>Suppose you meet a native who you believe is a knight, and the native says, "You will never believe that I have a pot of gold." What do you believe? Explain.</li>
							<li>Suppose you meet a native who you believe is a knight; explain why you believe whatever the native says.</li>
						</ol>
					</statement>
					<solution>
						<ol>
							<li>Yes, you would believe the knight and go searching for gold.</li>
							<li>No, you would not believe the knave, so you would not go searching for gold.</li>
							<li>No. If a knight said it, they would be lying, and if a knave said it, they would be telling the truth, so neither native could say it.</li>
							<li>You believe the native is telling the truth, so you believe they have a pot of gold.</li>
							<li>You will will believe what the native says, so you will not believe that the native has a pot of gold.</li>
							<li>You believe knights to tell the truth, so you will believe whatever the native says.</li>
						</ol>
					</solution>
				</activity>
				
				
				<p>
					Our main focus of study in what follows is the statement "You will never believe that I am a knight," made by a native of Smullyan Island<fn>Again, we owe a debt to the <url href="https://www.artofmathematics.org">Discovering the Art of Mathematics</url> project.</fn>.
					In order to draw appropriate conclusions, we will need to be outside the system, so we will consider a reasoner named Raymond as he interacts with natives on Smullyan Island.
					We will first deal with a Raymond who believes he is incapable of making a mistake; that is, if Raymond believes a particular statement, then, as far as he is concerned, the statement is really true.
					For example, if Raymond ever believes that a native is a knight, then because he thinks he is incapable of making mistakes, he concludes that the native really is a night and therefore that everything that person says is true.
				</p>
				
				<exploration xml:id="expl-consistent">
					<statement>
						<p>
							Suppose Raymond believes he is incapable of making a mistake, and he meets a native who says, "You will never believe that I am a knight."
						</p>
						<ol>
							<li>Suppose Raymond begins with the case that the native is a knave. What can he conclude from the native's statement?</li>
							<li>Based on your answer to the previous question and the fact that Raymond thinks he is incapable of making mistakes, what does he conclude the native to be? Explain.</li>
							<li>Explain why your answer to the previous question gives rise to a contradiction.</li>
							<li>What does your answer to Questions 2-3 mean about Raymond's assumption that the native is a knave? Explain.</li>
							<li>Based on your reasoning thus far, what does Raymond now believe the native to be?</li>
							<li>Based on the native's statement, "You will never believe I am a knight," what is the true status of the native? Explain.</li>
							<li>Based on your answers to this exploration, explain why a reasoner who believes they are accurate and who meets a native who says, "You will never believe that I am a knight" will eventually become inaccurate.</li>
						</ol>
					</statement>
					<solution>
						<ol>
							<li>If Raymond assumes for the moment that the native is knave, he will believe the native is lying. Thus, he will believe that the native is a knight.</li>
							<li>A knight.</li>
							<li>Raymond began by assuming the native is a knave and concluded that he is a knight. This is a contradiction, as the native cannot be both.</li>
							<li>It's incorrect, as it leads to a contradiction, and Raymond does not believe he is capable of making mistakes.</li>
							<li>Raymond now believes the native is a knight.</li>
							<li>The native is a knight, as the belief that he is a knave, together with his statement, leads to a contradiction.</li>
							<li>If Raymond believes the native is a knight, he will believe the native's statement, and stop believing the native is a knight, leading him to be inaccurate</li>
						</ol>

					</solution>
				</exploration>

				<p>
					In the next exploration, we'll assume that Raymond is <term>regular</term>, meaning that it is impossible for him to believe a proposition <m>P</m> and, at the same time, believe that he does not believe <m>P</m>.
					As before, Raymond goes to Smullyan Island and meets a native who says, "You will never believe that I am a knight."
				</p>

				<exploration xml:id="expl-regular">
					<statement>
						<ol>
							<li>Suppose Raymond believes the native is a knight.  Then what will Raymond also believe? Explain.</li>
							<li>Since Raymond is regular, what does your answer to the previous question mean about his original belief that the native is a knight? Explain.</li>
							<li>Based on your answer to the previous question, what will Raymond now believe to be the type of the native? Explain.</li>
							<li>Based on your answer to the previous question, is the native's original statement true or false? Explain.</li>
							<li>Based on your answer to the previous question, what does Raymond now believe to be the type of the native? Explain.</li>
							<li>Based on your answers to Questions 2 and 4, is Raymond regular? Explain.</li>
						</ol>
					</statement>
					<solution>
						<ol>
							<li>If Raymond believes the native is a knight, he will believe what the native tells him.</li>
							<li>Let <m>P</m> be the statement "I (the native) am a knight". Then Raymond believes <m>P</m>, which means he believes the native's statement, which is that he does not believe <m>P</m>. This is a contradiction, as Raymond is regular.</li>
							<li>He now believes the native is a knave.</li>
							<li>Raymond believes the native's statement is false.</li>
							<li>Since Raymond believes the native's statement is false, he does not believe that he will never believe the native is a knight. Thus, he does not believe that he believes that the native is a knave.</li>
							<li>No. In either case he begins by believing the native is one thing, and eventually believes that he does not believe it.</li> 
						</ol>

					</solution>

				</exploration>

				<p>
					The primary takeaway from <xref ref="expl-regular" /> is that it is possible, assuming the rules of Smullyan Island hold, for a person to both believe and not believe something. This is the heart of Godel's Incompleteness Theorems.
					Before we explore Godel's First Incompleteness Theorem, we make a definition.
				</p>
				
				<definition>
					<p>
						A reasoner is said to be <term>inconsistent</term> if there is some statement <m>P</m> such that the reasoner believes both <m>P</m> and <m>\neg P</m>.
						We call a reasoner <term>consistent</term> if there is no statement <m>P</m> such that the reasoner believes both <m>P</m> and <m>\neg P</m>.
					</p>
				</definition>


				<exploration xml:id="expl-godelfirst">
					<title>Godel's First Incompleteness Theorem via Knights and Knaves</title>
						<statement>
							<p>
								A normal<fn>A reasoner is normal if whenever he believes a statement, then he believes that he believes it.</fn> consistent stable<fn>A reasoner is stable if whenever he believes that he believes a statement, then he believes it.</fn> reasoner named Raymond visits Smullyan Island and meets a native who says, "You will never believe that I am a knight".
							</p>
							<ol>
								<li>Suppose that Raymond believes the native is a knight. Explain why it is reasonable to conclude that that Raymond believes that he believes the native is a knight.</li>
								<li>Since Raymond believes that the native is a knight, what must he also believe, based on what the native said? Explain.</li>
								<li>Explain why your answers to Questions 1-2 show that Raymond will thus never actually believe the native is a knight since he is consistent.</li>
								<li>Alternatively, suppose that Raymond at some point believes that the native is a knave. What must he also believe, based on what the native said? Explain</li>
								<li>Explain why your answers to questions 4-5 show that Raymond will thus never actually believe the native is a knave since he is consistent.</li>
								<li>Use your answers to questions 1-6 to explain why Raymond will never believe that the native is a knight nor that this native is a knave.</li>
								<li>Explain why, despite your answer to the previous question, we know that the native must be either a knight or a knave.</li>
							</ol>
						</statement>
						<solution>
							<ol>
								<li>Raymond is normal.</li>
								<li>That the native told the truth.</li>
								<li>Since Raymond is consistent, he cannot both believe the native is a knight, and not believe that the native is a knight. So, he cannot believe the native's statement.</li>
								<li>If he believes the native is a knave, he will not believe the native's statement. Thus, he does not believe that he will never believe the native is a knight. That is, he believes he will believe that the native is a knight, and since he is stable, he believes the native is a knight.</li>
								<li>Since Raymond is consistent, he can't both believe the native is a knave and not believe the native is a knave. Thus, he cannot believe the native is a knave.</li>
								<li>When Raymond believes the native is a knight, he eventually believes he is not a knight, which is a contradiction. Similarly if Raymond believes the native is a knave. Thus, he cannot ever believe either, as he is consistent.</li>
								<li>The native is a native of the Island, and so, if the rules of the island are to be believed, must be a knight or a knave.</li>
							</ol>

						</solution>

					</exploration>
	
	
		<p>
			<xref ref="expl-godelfirst" /> illustrates Godel's First Incompleteness Theorem, which revolutionized 20th century mathematical logic.
		</p>

		<assemblage>
		  		<title>Godel's First Incompleteness Theorem</title>
		  			
		  			<p>
		  				A normal, consistent, stable reasoner of type 1<fn>A reasoner is <term>type 1</term> if she believes all tautologies (propositions that can be established purely on the basis of truth tables for the logical connectives) and believes in <em>modus ponens</em>: whenever <m>P</m> and <m>P\Rightarrow Q</m> are true, <m>Q</m> is true.</fn> comes to the island and believes the rules of the island.
		  				She meets a native who says: "You will never believe that I am a knight". Then the reasoner's belief system is incomplete.
		  				That is, the reasoner will never believe that the native is a knight, and will never believe that the native is not a knight.
					</p>
		  	</assemblage>
		  	
		  	<p>
		  		Informally, this theorem states that any <em>sufficiently strong</em> consistent formal system contains undecidable statements.
		  		That is, there are sensible statements that one can make which cannot be proved from within the system.
		  		In that case, we may adopt the undecidable statement <em>or its negation</em> as an additional axiom without causing any contradiction.

		  	</p>
		  	
		  	<p>
		  		It may not surprise you to learn that there is a second incompleteness theorem, which we now state.
		  	</p>

<worksheet>
			
	<assemblage>
		  		<title>Godel's Second Incompleteness Theorem</title>
		  			
		  			<p>
		  				A reasoner of type 4<fn>Definition omitted.</fn> visits the island and meets a native who says: "You will never believe that I am a knight."
		  				Then, if the reasoner is consistent, she can never know that she is consistent.
		  				Stated another way, if the reasoner ever believes that she cannot be inconsistent, she will become inconsistent.
					</p>
		  	</assemblage>
		  	
		  	<p>
		  		Informally, Godel's Second Incompleteness Theorem states that no consistent formal system can prove its own consistency.
		  		We thus obtain limitations on the formal axiomatic approach to mathematics.
		  		Any consistent set of axioms and rules of inference strong enough to include arithmetic must contain undecidable statements.
		  		Furthermore, no sufficiently strong formal system can establish its own consistency!
		  		</p>

			<principle>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Godel's theorems leave mathematicians and students of mathematics in a precarious state. Consider the following questions in your groups.
					</p>
					<ol>
						<li>Godel's first theorem implies that that are mathematical questions that do not have "one right answer". What do you think of this? If you're a future teacher, what implications, if any, does this have for your work?</li>
						<li>Godel's second theorem implies that the consistency of mathematics is taken as an article of faith. This, despite the elevated role that mathematical proof and/or quantitative justifications have in modern society. Discuss.</li>
					</ol>
				</statement>
			</principle>
			
			<p>
				The eagle-eyed reader might note that Godel's first incompleteness theorem implies that there are undecidable statements, but the statement of the theorem does not give an example of such a statement.
				In order to see such a statement in context, we'll turn to an exploration of infinity. First, a definition.
			</p>
			
			<definition>
				<p>
					Let <m>S</m> and <m>T</m> be <term>sets</term>, which we may think of as collections of objects.
					We say that <m>S</m> and <m>T</m> have the same <term>cardinality</term> if there is a one-to-one correspondence between the objects of <m>S</m> and those of <m>T</m>, i.e., if each element of <m>S</m> can be paired up with one and only one unique element of <m>T</m>.
					In this case, we write <m>|S| = |T|</m>.
				</p>
			</definition>
			
			<activity>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Let <m>S = \{1,2,3,4\}</m>, <m>T=\{\square,\circ,\bigstar,\triangle\}</m>, and <m>U = \{\diamondsuit,\spadesuit,\clubsuit\}</m>.
					</p>
					<ol>
						<li>Can you find a one-to-one correspondence between <m>S</m> and <m>T</m>? Describe it, or explain why none exist.</li>
						<li>Can you find a one-to-one correspondence between <m>S</m> and <m>U</m>? Describe it, or explain why none exist.</li>
						<li>Can you find a one-to-one correspondence between <m>T</m> and <m>U</m>? Describe it, or explain why none exist.</li>
					</ol>
				</statement>
			</activity>
			
			<p>
				In order to explore our undecidable statement, we need to set some notation.
			</p>

			<definition xml:id="def-number_sets">
				<p>
					We define the following sets of numbers.
				</p>
				<ol>
					<li>The <term>natural numbers</term> are given by <m>\mathbb{N} = \{1, 2, 3, \ldots\}</m>.</li>
					<li>The <term>whole numbers</term> are given by <m>\mathbb{W} = \{0,1,2,3,\ldots\}</m>.</li>
					<li>The <term>integers</term> are given by <m>\mathbb{Z} = \{\ldots, -3, -2, -1, 0, 1, 2, 3, \ldots\}</m>.</li>
					<li>The <term>even integers</term> are given by <m>2\mathbb{Z} = \{\ldots, -6, -4, -2, 0, 2, 4, 6, \ldots\}</m>.</li>
					<li>The set of <term>rational numbers</term> is denoted by <m>\mathbb{Q}</m> and consists of all fractions <m>\frac{a}{b}</m>, where <m>a,b</m> are integers and <m>b\ne 0</m>.</li>
					<li>The set of <term>real numbers</term> is denoted by <m>\mathbb{R}</m> and is given by all positive and negative infinite decimals (alternatively, every point on the number line).</li>
				</ol>
				</definition>

			<activity>
				<statement>
					<p>
						For the numbers that follow, identify all sets described in <xref ref="def-number_sets" /> they live in.
					</p>
					<ol>
						<li> <m>7</m></li>
						<li><m>-2</m></li>
						<li><m>\pi</m></li>
						<li><m>\frac{4}{3}</m></li>
						<li><m>0</m></li>
					</ol>
				</statement>
			</activity>

			<p>
				We now look for some one-to-one correspondences.
			</p>

			<exploration xml:id="expl-countable">
				<statement>
					<p>
						For the following pairs of sets, determine whether a one-to-one correspondence between the two sets exists. If it does, describe it. If it does not, give a justification.
					</p>
					<ol>
						<li><m>\mathbb{N}</m> and <m>\mathbb{W}</m></li>
						<li><m>\mathbb{W}</m> and <m>\mathbb{Z}</m></li>
						<li><m>\mathbb{Z}</m> and <m>2\mathbb{Z}</m></li>
						<li><m>\mathbb{N}</m> and <m>2\mathbb{Z}</m></li>
						<li>(Challenge) <m>\mathbb{N}</m> and <m>\mathbb{Q}</m></li>
					</ol>
				</statement>
			</exploration>
			
			<exploration xml:id="expl-uncountable">
				<statement>
					<p>
